---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { withBase } from "../lib/urls";
---

<BaseLayout title="About | UNLV ECON 495 Journal" bodyClass="section-about page-about">
  <section class="page-intro page-intro--band full-bleed">
    <div class="page-intro-title">
      <h1>About the Proceedings</h1>
    </div>
    <div class="page-intro-subtitle">
      <p>
        The <strong>UNLV ECON 495 Capstone Proceedings</strong> is an open-access archive of undergraduate working papers
        produced in <strong>ECON 495 (Seminar in Economic Research)</strong> at the University of Nevada, Las Vegas.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each semester is released as a single <strong>issue</strong> so student research remains
        <strong>citable, discoverable, and easy to browse</strong>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="content-section">
    <section class="about-two-col">
      <article class="prose-section about-panel">
        <h2>Mission and Scope</h2>
        <p>
          The Proceedings exists to preserve and showcase the capstone research process, turning an economic question into
          <strong>evidence, analysis, and a defensible argument</strong>.
        </p>
        <p>
          It expands access to undergraduate scholarship while providing student authors a durable public record of their work.
        </p>
        <p>
          Papers posted here are <strong>working papers</strong>, not peer-reviewed journal articles. Authors may revise drafts
          as methods, writing, and interpretation improve over time.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="prose-section about-panel">
        <h2>Archive Organization</h2>
        <p>The archive is structured to make research easy to find and cite:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Issues (by semester):</strong> Each semester is published as one issue.</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Paper pages:</strong> Each paper has its own page with an abstract, key metadata, and a downloadable PDF.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Categories (by topic):</strong> Papers are indexed by topic category across semesters for discovery and
            browsing.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Many ECON 495 projects are also presented in the broader undergraduate research ecosystem at UNLV (for example,
          research symposia), and strong papers are well-positioned for further development into more formal publication
          pathways.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <hr class="section-divider" />

    <section class="prose-section">
      <h2>Editorial Leadership</h2>
      <div class="content-stack editorial-grid">
        <article class="founder-card">
          <img
            class="founder-thumb"
            src={withBase("/assets/images/assane.jpg")}
            alt="Professor Djeto Assane"
            style="--focus-y: 40%;"
          />
          <div class="founder-body">
            <h3 class="founder-name">Professor Djeto Assane, Ph.D.</h3>
            <p class="founder-role">ECON 495 Instructor</p>
            <p>
              Dr. Djeto Assane was educated at the Universit&eacute; d&apos;Abidjan (C&ocirc;te d&apos;Ivoire) and the University of
              Colorado Boulder (M.A., Ph.D.). His teaching areas include statistics, econometrics, mathematical economics, and
              microeconomics. He has also served as visiting faculty in the American Economic Association Summer Minority
              Scholarship Program.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="founder-card">
          <img
            class="founder-thumb"
            src={withBase("/assets/images/mark-jayson.jpg")}
            alt="Mark Jayson Farol"
            style="--focus-y: 35%;"
          />
          <div class="founder-body">
            <h3 class="founder-name">Mark Jayson Farol, M.A.</h3>
            <p class="founder-role">Journal Organizer</p>
            <p>
              Mark Jayson Farol earned his M.A. in Quantitative Business Economics and B.S. in Economics at UNLV. He previously
              supported undergraduate empirical research in ECON 495 as a graduate assistant and research collaborator, and
              organizes the Proceedings to keep student work accessible, organized, and citable.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="section-divider" />

    <section class="prose-section">
      <h2>Graduate Assistants</h2>
      <div class="content-stack assistants-grid">
        <article class="founder-card">
          <img
            class="founder-thumb"
            src={withBase("/assets/images/brandon-penticoff.jpg")}
            alt="Brandon Penticoff"
            style="--focus-y: 35%;"
          />
          <div class="founder-body">
            <h3 class="founder-name">Brandon Penticoff</h3>
            <p class="founder-role">Graduate Assistant, Spring 2026</p>
            <p>
              Brandon Penticoff is a University of Nevada, Las Vegas student pursuing an accelerated B.A./M.A. in Economics and
              Quantitative Business Economics. He works as a freelance Financial Data Analyst, transforming complex banking
              records into structured reports for legal- and policy-oriented analysis. Focus areas include data organization,
              litigation support, and clear communication of data-driven insights.
            </p>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <hr class="section-divider" />

    <section class="prose-section">
      <h2>Citation, Reuse, and Disclaimer</h2>
      <p>
        Unless otherwise noted, <strong>authors retain copyright</strong>. Posting on this site is intended to make student
        research discoverable and citable. For reuse beyond brief quotation, contact the author or the journal team.
      </p>
    </section>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
